# Loading Google Storage Data to HDFS
- The `wdi_gs` table we created points to a GS location, it would be more efficient for running queries if the data is stored in the HDFS.
- So now we are creating a new table (`wdi_csv_text`) and it is the same as wdi_gs but will be stored on HDFS
- Then we execute a SQL query to return row count twice. This query will run faster the second time as the file system cache holds data that was read from the disk the first time, making the second request get the data from cache instead of reading it from the disk again.
- If we clear the filesystem cache and execute the query again then it will be as fast as the first time we ran it as it will be reading from disk again.

## Hive vs Bash
- Finally, to see the difference in time, we can copy the `wdi_csv_text` HDFS file to our master node and run a bash command for row count and see the difference in time
- Theoretically our Hive sql command earlier should be twice as fast as the Bash command as it is distributed across two nodes but there might be some overhead affecting that.

## Discovering a Parsing Issue
- By running the first query below, we can see that there is a parsing issue with the idicatorcode column in our table
- In the third paragraph we create a debug table to show the entire row and see how and why we are having this parsing issue
- So `wdi_csv_text` right now uses LazySimpleSerDe which splits the lines with commas and incorrectly splits extra columns because of it.
- A solution to this is to use a smarter SerDe to handle CSV edge cases.
- Hive CSV SerDE is more powerful than the default LazySimpleSerde and can solve this parsing issue for us. 
- However, there is a trade off for this switch, which is the performance.

- Since we created a new table with OpenCSVSerde to solve our parsing issue, we now find out that each of the columns are treated as strings even with our non-string column types.

- Our first paragraph underneath shows that year column for example is an int but on the right (OpenCSV) its a string.
- Then we create a view on top of `wdi_opencsv_text` in the fourth paragraph to cast to correct column types.

# Columnar File Optimization
- Now lets optimize HQL query using columnar file which is another method for optimizing queries.
- This will change our table to be column oriented instead of row oriented which is what we have been doing so far.
- Duplicate column values can be grouped together and they just reference the containing rows.
- The size of the table should be much smaller compared to a row oriented table also.
- This reduces the amount of data that needs to be read and therefore increases performance.
- In the second paragraph we create our column oriented table and in the third, we load data from `wdi_opencsv_gs` to `wdi_csv_parquet`
- Next we can compare the file sizes of `wdi_csv_parquet` and `wdi_opencsv_text` and we see that it is much smaller
- Finally we can run some queries to compare runtimes, first we can see for rowcount it only took 15 seconds
- And for another query (2015 GDP Growth) it was also significantly faster at 8 seconds vs 73 seconds.
